{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619089"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:28:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:28:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16528"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16528"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0,0.2,0.03,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9219"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65591"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9219"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16528"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51030"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6087"},{"type":"tags","id":"10317"},{"type":"tags","id":"10334"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21858"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21861"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65591"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ELower motor neurons (LMNs) extend from the anterior horn of the spinal cord or brainstem nuclei to innervate skeletal muscles. Damage to these neurons results in characteristic clinical findings.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the clinical features of a lower motor neuron lesion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diminished reflexes and fasciculations","Increased muscle tone and hyperreflexia","Diminished reflexes and Babinski response","Fasciculations and spasticity","Hyperreflexia and muscle wasting"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA lower motor neuron lesion characteristically presents with \u003Cstrong\u003Ediminished reflexes and fasciculations\u003C/strong\u003E. Additional features include flaccid paralysis, muscle wasting, and decreased muscle tone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased muscle tone and hyperreflexia\u003C/strong\u003E - These are features of upper motor neuron lesions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiminished reflexes and Babinski response\u003C/strong\u003E - Babinski response is a sign of upper motor neuron lesions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFasciculations and spasticity\u003C/strong\u003E - Spasticity is a feature of upper motor neuron lesions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperreflexia and muscle wasting\u003C/strong\u003E - Hyperreflexia is a feature of upper motor neuron lesions, while muscle wasting occurs in lower motor neuron lesions\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELower motor neuron lesions interrupt the final common pathway between the nervous system and skeletal muscle, leading to denervation changes including fasciculations (spontaneous muscle twitches) and hyporeflexia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Lower motor neuron lesions cause decreased muscle tone, diminished reflexes, fasciculations, and muscle atrophy.","Upper motor neuron signs like Babinski response are absent in lower motor neuron lesions.","Fasciculations are spontaneous muscle twitches caused by spontaneous firing of motor units."],"references":["Javed K, Daly DT. Neuroanatomy, Lower Motor Neuron Lesion. 2023 Aug 14. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30969636.","Garg N, Park SB, Vucic S, Yiannikas C, Spies J, Howells J, Huynh W, Matamala JM, Krishnan AV, Pollard JD, Cornblath DR, Reilly MM, Kiernan MC. Differentiating lower motor neuron syndromes. J Neurol Neurosurg Psychiatry. 2017 Jun;88(6):474-483. doi: 10.1136/jnnp-2016-313526. Epub 2016 Dec 21. PMID: 28003344; PMCID: PMC5529975.","Ravits J, Stack J. The lower motor neuron homunculus. Brain. 2022 Nov 21;145(11):3727-3729. doi: 10.1093/brain/awac310. Erratum in: Brain. 2023 Feb 13;146(2):e12. doi: 10.1093/brain/awac383. PMID: 36029046; PMCID: PMC9679163.","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51030"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16528"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51030","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51030"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T15:50:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T11:56:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9219"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65591"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tag